  &lt;Comment&gt;
    &lt;Title&gt;My wife's recent hospital experience&lt;/Title&gt;
    &lt;ScreenName&gt;Barton&lt;/ScreenName&gt;
    &lt;CommentText&gt;My wife experienced excellent nursing and pain control in Southmead for the few days she was there following a fall down stairs in the home in which she fractured 2 ribs, burst a vertebrae, , damaged her aorta, and pelvis, and cut her forehead. Thankfully none of them necessitated surgery. Since her transfer to HDU and Gould Ward the high standard of nursing has continued, but we feel the control of pain has deteriorated. At the beginning of her care she had Lidocaine patches administered which helped considerably with pain control but the use of these had been banned, I believe by the Pharmacy Manager. I have spoken to a number of staff who told me that they used to be available.  
I have had them prescribed for my wife by the GP so they are now being applied to her but this was after a few days of being in considerable pain and consequently loss of sleep. I'm sure that you will be aware that intense pain is very debilitating and that this is likely to delay patients from discharge. I can only assume that senior management must be unaware of the situation and I would respectively suggest that something is done about it. I found it distressing to see my wife and others suffering, in my opinion unnecessarily.&lt;/CommentText&gt;
